to require the authenticate and confirmation factors to be the same. This reduces the security footprint slightly because it's just something that you possess in addition to something that you know.
However this reduces security because it makes brute force password attacks easier if the values can be determined by guessing. Passive attacks can be performed where a passive observer gathers the hashes and stores them for later brute forcing e.g. off the network in another country.
Ideally your authentication configuration should use passive authentication because it improves security and provides an audit trail through time. I will cover passive authentication later because it hasn't always been available in the configurations I've looked at.
Sometimes passive authentication isn't desirable. If you are configuring an authentication method that can only be satisfied through knowledge alone (something you know), you will want to store the authentication factors away from an attacker because that's a form of passive authentication.
